The sentence I find interesting in the AP article is:

``Banks, customers and businesses that still want paper checks could request a
substitute check, which has the same legal status as a regular one, to confirm
the electronic transfer.''

I may well be reading more into this than I should (and I admit that I've
been too lazy to read the actual legislation yet) but the implication is that
if you do not request (and receive) this substitute check then you do not have
anything with the same legal status as a canceled check. Going further out on
a limb, I'll bet that while this legislation allows the banks to substitute an
electronic transaction record/scan for a physical check, it grants no such
general right to consumers. (After all, consumers couldn't be trusted not to
fiddle with the bits, and it's too much bother to make them secure.) I further
assume that these substitute checks are not going to come free if you want them
on a regular basis, even if providing them would still cost less than the banks
are saving by not moving the original paper around. So my cynical take on the
change is that it is a way to shift some of the banks' business costs to the
customer in the name of overall efficiency.

Now, if the legislation provides for cryptographically signed images to be
delivered to the customer in digital form and further gives those images the
same legal status as physical checks by requiring that they be accepted as
proof of transaction (i.e., if the legislation does something to reduce the
_consumer's_ costs and/or increase the _consumer's_ convenience) I'll be happy
to withdraw my cynical comments. :)

Dan Lanciani
