I don't think it's about missing the physical checks per se--at least that's
not my objection. I'm all in favor of reducing clutter. The problem is that
we are seeing a paradigm shift being justified by a move to more efficient
electronic processing even though the latter really does not require the former.
This has been going on for quite a while, with the latest legislation merely
moving things along a bit faster.

The real problem is: who holds the burden-shifting token? Traditionally in
interactions between individual consumers and business or government, the
consumer's word doesn't count for much. If there is a dispute about a payment
the business or government is generally presumed to be correct (or at least
presumes itself correct) and the burden is on the consumer to show some proof.
Display of a canceled check by the consumer not only shifts the burden of proof
but also raises the bar considerably since the disputing party has to start
thinking in terms of fraud or forgery rather than asserting an oversight on the
part of the consumer. This in turn can encourage a more comprehensive search
of records (and file cabinet draws :) since it is no longer just a matter of
the consumer's word.

The move to electronic processing changes the nature of the token from a
piece of paper to some sort of electronically imaged document. I don't see
anything wrong with that in and of itself. But at the same time we are being
told that we will no longer receive the token by default. We have to ask the
bank to create the token when we need it. There may be a cost associated with
such creation. The damages we can receive if the bank is unable to create the
token (say, for the addition I made to my house 30 years ago and now need to
show the IRS on audit of the sale) are likely very limited. Obviously I'm
supposed to request tokens immediately for transactions that might later be
of importance, but this certainly doesn't simplify my life. And I'll bet that
the fee will be set high enough to discourage my simply requesting tokens for
every transaction.

The notion of not providing the token by default (and potentially being able
to charge for it on demand) is being conflated with the move to electronic
processing in general. In reality it is just an additional cost savings for
the bank, plus a new revenue stream for issuing the tokens. If the electronic
form of the transaction is in fact secure (e.g., cryptographically signed image)
then the bank should deliver that by default and the law should give it status
equivalent to a canceled check. In other words, the electronic transaction
record should *be* the token. I'd be very happy to store my tokens on (backed
up) disk rather than in a file cabinet full of paper. If (as I suspect) the
electronic transactions are not &quot;self proving&quot; but instead rely on the bank's
trustworthyness when creating the token on demand then the bank should create
the tokens (&quot;substitute checks&quot;) every month and send them with the statement
just as they now send the canceled checks. Any other approach is just a sneaky
way to *further* increase savings/enhance profits beyond the (presumably) huge
windfall of not having to move the original paper around.

Dan Lanciani
ddl@danlan.*com

