If there is fraud then the statute of limitations doesn't run. You can
never be sure that the IRS won't suggest fraud (and there doesn't seem to
be any penalty for the IRS if they fail to find it) so I like to keep my
records forever. :) (N.B. I don't pretend to understand who has the burden
of proof if the IRS proposes that, e.g., a large expense from 10 years ago
was really a fraudulent fabrication. But I'm happier to be able to pull out
the canceled check than not...) There is also the case where the IRS claims
that the return was never filed (or at least never received). This means that
the statute never started to run, at least as far as the IRS is concerned.

At the moment, the entire paper records for every tax return, canceled
check, credit card bill, invoice, bank/brokerage statement, etc. that I've
ever received take up about four file cabinet draws. While I don't consider
this a serious burden, I'd be happy to switch to electronic storage on a few
DVDs as soon as the electronic form that I can hold and present (without the
involvement of a third-party acting as oracle) has the same legal status as
the paper version.

